	doi = {10.2514/6.1990-3178},
	abstract = {Artificial Intelligence (AI) systems, especially expert systems, have been or are being integrated with simulations. Simulation integration of AI systems is a useful tool for exercising and debugging rule-based/knowledge-based AI systems. One might expect, for example, to find one or more intelligence components (in the form of an expert system) integrated into a real-time flight simulator. These intelligent components might be inserted as instructors in a training simulator or as tactical decision aids for a pilot operating in an advanced cockpit. The Pilot’s Associate program is a good example of proposed on-board use of several expert systems in an advanced cockpit, with staged testing in flight simulators. When such expert systems are initially integrated, problems may show up in the presence of the real-time simulation which did not appear during expert systems developmen. Advances in computer technology have enabled significant gains in AI technology. This cross-feed of technologies has been generally supportive of AI system integration. The integration of an AI system presents a special set of problems. If nothing else, the executive nature of the AI system is asynchronous with respect to the simulation and the input/output is symbolic. This paper discusses sources of problems that arise from AI system integration as well as progress towards solution of these problems. A few sources are, for example: comlexity of communication interfaces, time delays in response to AI system advisories, use of dissimilar computers (AI system host with respect to simulation) and use of different languages or versions of the same language. © 1990 General Dynamics Corporation. All rights reserved.},
